The Warwolf Trebuchet. A Medieval Siege Engine.<br>
<br>
The early rocket pioneers used to employ catapults for gaining extra altitude from their models. Back in the middle ages huge siege engines were employed for knocking down castle walls. Large boulders were sent sailing through the sky from a distance beyond longbow range. Perhaps they were on to something.<br>
<br>
With todays fantastic new alloys and possibly a counterweight lifted into position with pneumatics, couldn't an object be accelerated to escape velocity? Forget the Jules Verne cannon with its monstrous barrel and explosives. Just use a long lever and a counter weight resembling a small mountain. Thwack! Your payload is in orbit. It would be big but the technology is really simple and relatively cheap. Could this work?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.globalgallery.com/images/aa-2366.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
Giant Catapult as envisioned by Leonardo Da Vinci.<br>
