<br>
A catapult as I see it would be useful for getting that payload to orbit. Perhaps even that wonderful elevator ballast. A big round boulder measuring a few thousand tons. Escape velocity is 7 miles per second I think. That puts your projectile on a trajectory which takes it away from the Earth. Small objects would melt up in the atmosphere but massive objects could survive mostly intact. Like an asteroid impact in reverse motion. Perhaps components of a large spacecraft encapsulated in a thick heatshielding material could survive. This could never take flimsy vehicles or people to space. It's simply hurling useful material off Earth. We would need a big arm and an even bigger countermass. The arm has to be strong enough so it won't snap under the force of the gravity engines operation. As Archimedes once said &quot;Give me a long enough lever and I will move the Earth&quot;. He mean't a long enough, strong enough lever. The problem is that the very weight of the arm might cause it to break without help from the huge centripetal force exerted on it. Using a combination of heatshields for the payload, super strong alloys for the arm and some innovative engineering it might be possible. Nasa has investigated Super Guns for launching payloads and believes they can be made to work. Catapults look even more intriguing. If we can get the end of a very long arm to reach 7 miles per second it will work. Not just once but repeatedly. Just lift the weight back up with pneumatics and place another payload projectile. Launch a hundred a day and it only costs the electricity used in the pneumatic lifters to reset the machine.<br>
One idea might even be to launch ramjets at mach 3 then switch on the engine. Perhaps maybe to launch a rocket at Mach 10 and engage it at maximum assent. We could place Orion sections in orbit for later assembly. I just don't know if such a simple machine is possible at our current tech. The engineering might be beyond us.   <br>
